[38;2;248;248;242m         If  no  [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--file[0m[38;2;248;248;242m option is provided to git config, use the file given by GIT_CONFIG as[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         if it were provided via [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--file[0m[38;2;248;248;242m. This variable has no effect on other  Git  commands,[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         and  is  mostly for historical compatibility; there is generally no reason to use it[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         instead of the [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--file[0m[38;2;248;248;242m option.[0m

[38;2;253;151;31mEXAMPLES[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     Given a .git/config like this:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         #[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         # This is the config file, and[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         # a '#' or ';' character indicates[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         # a comment[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         #[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         ; core variables[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         [core][0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 ; Don't trust file modes[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 filemode = false[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         ; Our diff algorithm[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         [diff][0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 external = /usr/local/bin/diff-wrapper[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 renames = true[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         ; Proxy settings[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         [core][0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 gitproxy=proxy-command for kernel.org[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 gitproxy=default-proxy ; for all the rest[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         ; HTTP[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         [http][0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 sslVerify[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         [http "https://weak.example.com"][0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 sslVerify = false[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m                 cookieFile = /tmp/cookie.txt[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     you can set the filemode to true with[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config set core.filemode true[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     The hypothetical proxy command entries actually have a postfix to discern what URL  they[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     apply to. Here is how to change the entry for kernel.org to "ssh".[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config set [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--value[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31m'for[0m[38;2;248;248;242m kernel.org$' core.gitproxy '"ssh" for kernel.org'[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     This makes sure that only the key/value pair for kernel.org is replaced.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     To delete the entry for renames, do[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config unset diff.renames[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     If  you  want  to delete an entry for a multivar (like core.gitproxy above), you have to[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     provide a regex matching the value of exactly one line.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     To query the value for a given key, do[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config get core.filemode[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     or, to query a multivar:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config get [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--value[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31m"for[0m[38;2;248;248;242m kernel.org$" core.gitproxy[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     If you want to know all the values for a multivar, do:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config get [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--all[0m[38;2;248;248;242m [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--show-names[0m[38;2;248;248;242m core.gitproxy[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     If you like to live dangerously, you can replace all core.gitproxy by a new one with[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config set [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--all[0m[38;2;248;248;242m core.gitproxy ssh[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     However, if you really only want to replace the line for the default proxy, i.e. the one[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     without a "for ..." postfix, do something like this:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config set [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--value[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31m'![0m[38;2;248;248;242m for ' core.gitproxy ssh[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     To actually match only values with an exclamation mark, you have to[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config set [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--value[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31m'[![0m[38;2;248;248;242m]' section.key value[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     To add a new proxy, without altering any of the existing ones, use[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config set [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--append[0m[38;2;248;248;242m core.gitproxy '"proxy-command" for example.com'[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     An example to use customized color from the configuration in your script:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         #!/bin/sh[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         WS=$(git config get [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--type[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31mcolor[0m[38;2;248;248;242m [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--default[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31m"blue[0m[38;2;248;248;242m reverse" color.diff.whitespace)[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         RESET=$(git config get [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--type[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31mcolor[0m[38;2;248;248;242m [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--default[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31m"reset"[0m[38;2;248;248;242m "")[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         echo "${WS}your whitespace color or blue reverse${RESET}"[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     For URLs in https://weak.example.com, http.sslVerify is set to false, while it is set to[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     true for all others:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config get [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--type[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31mbool[0m[38;2;248;248;242m [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--url[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31mhttps://good[0m[38;2;248;248;242m.example.com http.sslverify[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         true[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config get [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--type[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31mbool[0m[38;2;248;248;242m [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--url[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31mhttps://weak[0m[38;2;248;248;242m.example.com http.sslverify[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         false[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         % git config get [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--url[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31mhttps://weak[0m[38;2;248;248;242m.example.com http[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         http.cookieFile /tmp/cookie.txt[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         http.sslverify false[0m

[38;2;253;151;31mCONFIGURATION FILE[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     The Git configuration file contains a number of variables that affect the Git  commands'[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     behavior.  The  files .git/config and optionally config.worktree (see the "CONFIGURATION[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     FILE" section of [0m[38;2;166;226;46mgit-worktree[0m[38;2;249;38;114m([0m[38;2;190;132;255m1[0m[38;2;249;38;114m)[0m[38;2;248;248;242m) in each repository are used to store the configuration[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     for that repository, and [0m[38;2;255;255;255m$[0m[38;2;190;132;255mHOME[0m[38;2;248;248;242m/.gitconfig is used to store a per-user  configuration  as[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     fallback values for the .git/config file. The file /etc/gitconfig can be used to store a[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     system-wide default configuration.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     The  configuration  variables  are  used by both the Git plumbing and the porcelain com‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     mands. The variables are divided into sections, wherein  the  fully  qualified  variable[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     name  of  the  variable itself is the last dot-separated segment and the section name is[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     everything before the last dot. The variable names are case-insensitive, allow only  al‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     phanumeric characters and -, and must start with an alphabetic character. Some variables[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     may appear multiple times; we say then that the variable is multivalued.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m   Syntax[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     The  syntax is fairly flexible and permissive. Whitespace characters, which in this con‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     text are the space character (SP) and the horizontal tabulation  (HT),  are  mostly  ig‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     nored.  The  #  and  ; characters begin comments to the end of line. Blank lines are ig‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     nored.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     The file consists of sections and variables. A section begins with the name of the  sec‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     tion  in  square brackets and continues until the next section begins. Section names are[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     case-insensitive. Only alphanumeric characters, - and . are allowed  in  section  names.[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     Each  variable  must  belong  to  some section, which means that there must be a section[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     header before the first setting of a variable.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     Sections can be further divided into subsections. To begin a subsection put its name  in[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     double  quotes, separated by space from the section name, in the section header, like in[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     the example below:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m                 [section "subsection"][0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     Subsection names are case sensitive and can contain any characters  except  newline  and[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     the  null  byte.  Doublequote " and backslash can be included by escaping them as \" and[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     \\, respectively. Backslashes preceding other characters are dropped when  reading;  for[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     example,  \t  is  read  as  t  and \0 is read as 0. Section headers cannot span multiple[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     lines. Variables may belong directly to a section or to a given subsection. You can have[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     [section] if you have [section "subsection"], but you don’t need to.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     There is also a deprecated [section.subsection] syntax. With this syntax, the subsection[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     name is converted to lower-case and is also compared case sensitively. These  subsection[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     names follow the same restrictions as section names.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     All  the other lines (and the remainder of the line after the section header) are recog‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     nized as setting variables, in the  form  name  =  value  (or  just  name,  which  is  a[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     short-hand  to  say  that  the  variable  is the boolean "true"). The variable names are[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     case-insensitive, allow only alphanumeric characters and -, and must start with  an  al‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     phabetic character.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     Whitespace  characters  surrounding name, = and value are discarded. Internal whitespace[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     characters within value are retained verbatim. Comments starting with either # or ;  and[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     extending to the end of line are discarded. A line that defines a value can be continued[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     to  the  next  line by ending it with a backslash (\); the backslash and the end-of-line[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     characters are discarded.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     If value needs to contain leading or trailing whitespace characters, it must be enclosed[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     in double quotation marks ("). Inside double quotation marks, double quote (") and back‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     slash (\) characters must be escaped: use \" for " and \\ for \.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     The following escape sequences (beside \" and \\) are recognized: \n for newline charac‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     ter (NL), \t for horizontal tabulation (HT, TAB) and \b for backspace (BS).  Other  char[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     escape sequences (including octal escape sequences) are invalid.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m   Includes[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     The  include  and includeIf sections allow you to include config directives from another[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     source. These sections behave identically to each other  with  the  exception  that  in‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     cludeIf  sections may be ignored if their condition does not evaluate to true; see "Con‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     ditional includes" below.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     You can include a config file from another by setting the special include.path  (or  in‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     cludeIf.*.path)  variable  to  the name of the file to be included. The variable takes a[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     pathname as its value, and is subject to tilde expansion. These variables can  be  given[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     multiple times.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     The contents of the included file are inserted immediately, as if they had been found at[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     the  location of the include directive. If the value of the variable is a relative path,[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     the path is considered to be relative to the configuration file in which the include di‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     rective was found. See below for examples.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m   Conditional includes[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     You can conditionally include a config file from another by setting an includeIf.<condi‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     tion>.path variable to the name of the file to be included.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     The condition starts with a keyword followed by a colon and some data whose  format  and[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     meaning depends on the keyword. Supported keywords are:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     gitdir[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         The  data  that follows the keyword gitdir and a colon is used as a glob pattern. If[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         the location of the .git directory matches the pattern,  the  include  condition  is[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         met.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         The  .git  location  may be auto-discovered, or come from [0m[38;2;255;255;255m$[0m[38;2;190;132;255mGIT_DIR[0m[38;2;248;248;242m environment vari‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         able. If the repository is auto-discovered via a .git file (e.g. from submodules, or[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         a linked worktree), the .git location would be the final location where the .git di‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         rectory is, not where the .git file is.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         The pattern can contain standard globbing wildcards and two additional ones, **/ and[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         [0m[38;2;117;113;94m/*[0m[38;2;117;113;94m*, that can match multiple path components. Please refer to gitignore(5)  for  de‐[0m
[38;2;117;113;94m         tails. For convenience:[0m

[38;2;117;113;94m         •   If the pattern starts with ~/, ~ will be substituted with the content of the en‐[0m
[38;2;117;113;94m             vironment variable HOME.[0m

[38;2;117;113;94m         •   If  the pattern starts with ./, it is replaced with the directory containing the[0m
[38;2;117;113;94m             current config file.[0m

[38;2;117;113;94m         •   If the pattern does not start with either ~/, ./ or /, *[0m[38;2;117;113;94m*/[0m[38;2;248;248;242m will be automatically[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m             prepended[0m[38;2;248;248;242m.[0m[38;2;248;248;242m For example[0m[38;2;248;248;242m,[0m[38;2;248;248;242m the pattern foo[0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242mbar becomes [0m[38;2;249;38;114m*[0m[38;2;248;248;240m*/[0m[38;2;248;248;242mfoo[0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242mbar and  would  match[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m             [0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242many[0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242mpath[0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242mto[0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242mfoo[0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242mbar[0m[38;2;248;248;242m.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         •   If  the  pattern  ends  with [0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242m,[0m[38;2;248;248;242m [0m[38;2;249;38;114m*[0m[38;2;249;38;114m*[0m[38;2;248;248;242m will be automatically added[0m[38;2;248;248;242m.[0m[38;2;248;248;242m For example[0m[38;2;248;248;242m,[0m[38;2;248;248;242m the[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m             pattern foo[0m[38;2;249;38;114m/[0m[38;2;248;248;242m becomes foo[0m[38;2;117;113;94m/*[0m[38;2;117;113;94m*. In other words, it matches "foo" and everything in‐[0m
[38;2;117;113;94m             side, recursively.[0m

[38;2;117;113;94m     gitdir/i[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         This is the same as gitdir except that matching is done case-insensitively (e.g.  on[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         case-insensitive file systems)[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     onbranch[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         The data that follows the keyword onbranch and a colon is taken to be a pattern with[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         standard  globbing  wildcards  and  two additional ones, **/ and /**, that can match[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         multiple path components. If we are in a worktree where the name of the branch  that[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         is currently checked out matches the pattern, the include condition is met.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         If the pattern ends with /, ** will be automatically added. For example, the pattern[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         foo/  becomes  foo/**. In other words, it matches all branches that begin with foo/.[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         This is useful if your branches are organized hierarchically and you would  like  to[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         apply a configuration to all the branches in that hierarchy.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     hasconfig:remote.*.url[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         The  data  that follows this keyword and a colon is taken to be a pattern with stan‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         dard globbing wildcards and two additional ones, **/ and /**, that can match  multi‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         ple  components.  The  first time this keyword is seen, the rest of the config files[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         will be scanned for remote URLs (without applying any values). If  there  exists  at[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         least one remote URL that matches this pattern, the include condition is met.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         Files  included  by  this option (directly or indirectly) are not allowed to contain[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         remote URLs.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         Note that unlike other includeIf conditions, resolving this condition relies on  in‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         formation that is not yet known at the point of reading the condition. A typical use[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         case  is this option being present as a system-level or global-level config, and the[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         remote URL being in a local-level config; hence the need to scan ahead when  resolv‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         ing  this  condition.  In order to avoid the chicken-and-egg problem in which poten‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         tially-included files can affect whether such files are  potentially  included,  Git[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         breaks  the  cycle by prohibiting these files from affecting the resolution of these[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         conditions (thus, prohibiting them from declaring remote URLs).[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         As for the naming of this keyword, it is for forwards compatibility  with  a  naming[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         scheme  that supports more variable-based include conditions, but currently Git only[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         supports the exact keyword described above.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     A few more notes on matching via gitdir and gitdir/i:[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     •   Symlinks in [0m[38;2;255;255;255m$[0m[38;2;190;132;255mGIT_DIR[0m[38;2;248;248;242m are not resolved before matching.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     •   Both the symlink & realpath versions of paths will be matched outside  of  [0m[38;2;255;255;255m$[0m[38;2;190;132;255mGIT_DIR[0m[38;2;248;248;242m.[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         E.g.  if  ~/git  is  a  symlink  to  /mnt/storage/git,  both  gitdir:~/git  and git‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         dir:/mnt/storage/git will match.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         This was not the case in the initial release of this feature in v2.13.0, which  only[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         matched  the  realpath  version.  Configuration that wants to be compatible with the[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         initial release of this feature needs to either specify only the  realpath  version,[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         or both versions.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     •   Note  that "../" is not special and will match literally, which is unlikely what you[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         want.[0m

