[38;2;248;248;242m   Values[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     Values of many variables are treated as a simple string, but there  are  variables  that[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m     take values of specific types and there are rules as to how to spell them.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     boolean[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         When a variable is said to take a boolean value, many synonyms are accepted for true[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         and false; these are all case-insensitive.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         true[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m             Boolean true literals are yes, on, true, and 1. Also, a variable defined without[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m             = <value> is taken as true.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         false[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m             Boolean false literals are no, off, false, 0 and the empty string.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         When  converting a value to its canonical form using the [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--type[0m[38;2;249;38;114m=[0m[38;2;253;151;31mbool[0m[38;2;248;248;242m type specifier,[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         git config will ensure that the output is "true" or "false" (spelled in lowercase).[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     integer[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         The value for many variables that specify various sizes  can  be  suffixed  with  k,[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         M,... to mean "scale the number by 1024", "by 1024x1024", etc.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     color[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         The  value  for  a variable that takes a color is a list of colors (at most two, one[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         for foreground and one for background) and attributes (as many as you  want),  sepa‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         rated by spaces.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         The  basic  colors  accepted  are  normal, black, red, green, yellow, blue, magenta,[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         cyan, white and default. The first color given is the foreground; the second is  the[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         background.  All  the  basic  colors except normal and default have a bright variant[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         that can be specified by prefixing the color with bright, like brightred.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         The color normal makes no change to the color. It is the same as  an  empty  string,[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         but  can  be  used  as the foreground color when specifying a background color alone[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         (for example, "normal red").[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         The color default explicitly resets the color to the terminal default,  for  example[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         to  specify a cleared background. Although it varies between terminals, this is usu‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         ally not the same as setting to "white black".[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         Colors may also be given as numbers between 0 and 255; these use ANSI 256-color mode[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         (but note that not all terminals may support this). If your  terminal  supports  it,[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         you  may  also  specify 24-bit RGB values as hex, like #ff0ab3, or 12-bit RGB values[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         like #f1b, which is equivalent to the 24-bit color #ff11bb.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         The accepted attributes are bold, dim, ul, blink, reverse, italic, and  strike  (for[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         crossed-out or "strikethrough" letters). The position of any attributes with respect[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         to  the  colors  (before, after, or in between), doesn’t matter. Specific attributes[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         may be turned off by prefixing them with no or no- (e.g., noreverse, no-ul, etc).[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         The pseudo-attribute reset resets all colors  and  attributes  before  applying  the[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         specified  coloring.  For example, reset green will result in a green foreground and[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         default background without any active attributes.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         An empty color string produces no color effect at all. This can  be  used  to  avoid[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         coloring specific elements without disabling color entirely.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         For  git’s  pre-defined color slots, the attributes are meant to be reset at the be‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         ginning of each item in the colored  output.  So  setting  color.decorate.branch  to[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         black  will  paint  that branch name in a plain black, even if the previous thing on[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         the same output line (e.g. opening parenthesis before the list of  branch  names  in[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         log  [0m[38;2;166;226;46m--decorate[0m[38;2;248;248;242m output) is set to be painted with bold or some other attribute. How‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         ever, custom log formats may do more  complicated  and  layered  coloring,  and  the[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         negated forms may be useful there.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m     pathname[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         A  variable  that takes a pathname value can be given a string that begins with "~/"[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         or "~user/", and the usual tilde expansion happens to such a string: ~/ is  expanded[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         to the value of [0m[38;2;255;255;255m$[0m[38;2;190;132;255mHOME[0m[38;2;248;248;242m, and ~user/ to the specified user’s home directory.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         If a path starts with %(prefix)/, the remainder is interpreted as a path relative to[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         Git’s  "runtime  prefix",  i.e.  relative  to  the location where Git itself was in‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         stalled. For example, %(prefix)/bin/ refers to the directory in which the  Git  exe‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         cutable  itself  lives. If Git was compiled without runtime prefix support, the com‐[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         piled-in prefix will be substituted instead. In the unlikely event  that  a  literal[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         path  needs  to be specified that should not be expanded, it needs to be prefixed by[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         ./, like so: ./%(prefix)/bin.[0m

[38;2;248;248;242m         If prefixed with :(optional), the configuration variable is treated as  if  it  does[0m
[38;2;248;248;242m         not exist, if the named path does not exist.[0m

